post_text:
Emailed to parents:
Welcome Back! Today is the first day of school and all students should login to find important first day of school messages and information from their teachers. As a reminder, usernames have not changed for returning students. Student username is the last name (first six characters), first initial of first name followed by the last four digits of your student number. If you have forgotten your student ID, you can call the school office and they will provide it for you. If you are new to Anchor Bay or a kindergarten student, you should have received this information last week directly from your child's school.

Example Student: Jane Smith

SmithJ1234@absstudents.abs.misd.net

All passwords have been reset: Student20 (Password is case sensitive, so be sure to type a capital S).

Parent/Student Resources to help with login:

Video Tutorial: https://youtu.be/DuNCGhr_kmI
PDF Handout Getting Started with Schoology for Students (1).pdf
District Website Link: https://www.anchorbay.misd.net/covid-19/student-schoology/

Secondary Parents,

We made a mistake! The letter sent earlier today stated that Secondary Student Schedules will be available in Schoology, when in fact it should have stated Parent Portal (PowerSchool). We apologize for the error.

Parents will be receiving schedule information directly from their child's secondary building on Wednesday after 3 p.m. (9/2).

Again, schedules will be in Parent Portal (PowerSchool) and students will not see their courses in Schoology until the first day of school, September 8th.

Thank you.

post_text:
Email sent to parents on August 20, 2020:

Anchor Bay Families,

On Wednesday evening, August 19th the Board of Education voted to begin the 2020 school year in a virtual setting for all students and to re-evaluate on October 2nd. Please know this is a postponement to the traditional, face-to-face option previously offered. The Board will continue to review and determine when it is appropriate to transition back to In-person instruction.

Our top priority remains the health and safety of our students and staff. The goal is to return to In-person instruction as it is the optimal learning environment for our students. Please watch for an email from the Technology Department that will be sent today providing information and next steps for parents.
Your continued patience and understanding is much appreciated as we navigate these uncertain times.

Leonard Woodside, Ed.S.
Superintendent

Reminder: To help parents better understand their choices and to provide a time for questions, we have scheduled three grade level-specific parent meetings. These meetings will go over the In-Person protocols such as how social distancing, schedules and cleaning will be addressed; as well as the Virtual Academy typical day, how Schoology will be used, time commitments and the role of the parent and teacher.

Middle and High School Parent Return to Learn Session will be Monday, August 17th at 6 p.m.

Elementary (K-5) Parent Return to Learn Session will be Tuesday, August 18th at 5 p.m.

Preschool Parent Return to Learn Session will be Tuesday, August 18th at 6 p.m.

Meeting information is available at https://www.anchorbay.misd.net/covid-19/

post_text:
8.6.2020 Letter to Parents:

Anchor Bay Families,

The Board of Education met yesterday evening (8/5) to review and determine the Fall start-up options. During the Public Comment portion of the meeting, some parents asked the Board to consider starting the school year fully remote for all students. The Board determined to meet again to consider this model. Please know that the registration for the Anchor Bay Virtual Academy has been postponed at this time. The Board will meet again early next week to review plans and make a final determination.

A lot of work has been accomplished since our last update on July 30th. Sub-committees of teachers, support staff, and administrators are continuing to work in the areas of safety, instruction and operations. Thank you to everyone who has written and shared your questions and concerns. We are responding to those emails and reviewing your input.

I will communicate the final plan once it is approved by the Board of Education.

Sincerely,

Leonard Woodside, Ed.S.

Superintendent

post_text:
Sunday, June 21, 2020, Father’s Day, Anchor Bay had several local teams Michigan BASS Nation High School Team Trail event #3 held at the Harrison Twp., MI Selfridge DNR Boat Launch - Lake St. Clair (U.S. Waters Only).
>>>>>>> master

Here are the results of our club kids:
• 6th place– teammates Connor Christensen and Noah Varitck, with volunteer boater Mike Varitek, had a 5 fish bag for 19.24 pounds (only 1.5 pounds away from 1st place!)
• 19th place – teammates Deveon Furtah and Nath Toureau, with volunteer boater Jed Toureau, had a 5 fish bag 16.43 pounds.
• 45th place – Aidan Pihaylic and Joey Elliott, with volunteer boater Shawn Elliott, had a 5 fish bag for 12.27 pounds.

Over 90 boats competed in the one-day event in two different divisions. The weather was hot with a high of 84 degrees and a 7-11 mph wind from the SE. This is an extremely competitive high school series that holds events on different lakes though the state, testing the angler’s skillsets. Great job to all the ABSD anglers that competed!

• 45th place – Aidan Pihaylic and Joey Elliott, with volunteer boater Shawn Elliott, had a 5 fish bag for 12.27 pounds.

post_text:
Congratulations to the Winners of the 2020 Michigan Bass Federation Junior State Championship!
>>>>>>> master

Aidan Pihaylic and Joey Elliott put together a 1st place finish on Sunday, June 28, 2020 to win the 2020 Michigan Bass Federation Junior State Championship!

The event was held on Pontiac Lake in Waterford Township, Michigan. The summer time fishing was extremely difficult due to the air temperature weas 84 degrees, hot, with little wind, 4-5 mph out of the North West, water temperatures well above the 70-degree mark. Joey and Aidan weighed in 5 largemouth bass, all alive for a sack of 9.95 pounds, with their large bass weighting in at 2.55 pounds. They caught over 20 fish on the day, most short, with only the 5 keepers.

The team will represent the state of Michigan at the 2020 TBF Junior World Championship (JWC) is set for July 29, 30, 31 on Mosquito Lake in Trumbull County Ohio.
text:
Congratulations to the Winners of the 2020 Michigan Bass Federation Junior State Championship!

Aidan Pihaylic and Joey Elliott put together a 1st place finish on Sunday, June 28, 2020 to win the 2020 Michigan Bass Federation Junior State Championship!

The event was held on Pontiac Lake in Waterford Township, Michigan. The summer time fishing was extremely difficult due to the air temperature weas 84 degrees, hot, with little wind, 4-5 mph out of the North West, water temperatures well above the 70-degree mark. Joey and Aidan weighed in 5 largemouth bass, all alive for a sack of 9.95 pounds, with their large bass weighting in at 2.55 pounds. They caught over 20 fish on the day, most short, with only the 5 keepers.

The team will represent the state of Michigan at the 2020 TBF Junior World Championship (JWC) is set for July 29, 30, 31 on Mosquito Lake in Trumbull County Ohio.

Rachel Hansen, a Early Childhood Special Education Teacher at Dean A. Naldrett Elementary, wanted to recognize her teacher-mentor:

PSA: long, sappy post alert. I feel so extremely blessed to have been placed with a mentor as wonderful as Cindy Bowman. Since I was hired in 2018, she has helped me to grow in every aspect of my life. She provides me daily guidance and has so many times stepped in using her experienced wisdom when she knew I could use her help. She has advocated for me, stepped up when she didn’t have to, and generously shares and gives anything she has. I learn so much from her and I know I can go to her with any and everything. She never attempts to make me conform to her way… More

post_text:
Anchor Bay High School will be hosting a Virtual Senior Scholarship Awards Program for 63 scholarship winners tonight at 6 p.m. This virtual format replaces the regular ceremony that usually takes place in May. Due to COVID-19, students were given more time to submit their scholarship applications for many local opportunities.
>>>>>>> master

The virtual program will feature 63 of our Anchor Bay High School graduates receiving scholarship money from the following organizations:
• Anchor Bay Community Foundation - $34,000
• JROTC - $8,000
• ABEA - $4,500
• Anchor Bay High School Staff Scholarships - $7,800
• Rotary - $1,000
• Anchor Bay Sports Booster - $4,800

These are not all the scholarships 2020 Anchor Bay graduates have received. Some organizations have delivered their scholarships directly to students’ homes. The district is waiting to compile a total of monies the Class of 2020 have received due to COVID-19 delays.

Congratulations!!!

Anchor Bay High School will be hosting a Virtual Senior Scholarship Awards Program for 63 scholarship winners tonight at 6 p.m. This virtual format replaces the regular ceremony that usually takes place in May. Due to COVID-19, students were given more time to submit their scholarship applications for many local opportunities.

The virtual program will feature 63 of our Anchor Bay High School graduates receiving scholarship money from the following organizations:
• Anchor Bay Community Foundation - $34,000
• JROTC - $8,000
• ABEA - $4,500
• Anchor Bay High School Staff Scholarships - $7,800
• Rotary - $1,000
• Anchor Bay Sports Booster - $4,800

These are not all the scholarships 2020 Anchor Bay graduates have received. Some organizations have delivered their scholarships directly to students’ homes. The district is waiting to compile a total of monies the Class of 2020 have received due to COVID-19 delays.

Congratulations!!!

JROTC Online Q&A Session
>>>>>>> master

Looking for a fun, challenging, and rewarding class to add to your schedule next year? Consider the JROTC. There is no military commitment and the experiences benefit students no matter what their life goals are!
Learn to be a drone pilot, compete with the drill team, or fly r/c aircraft! Also, learn academic skills to succeed in life regardless of whether you go straight to college, tradeschool, workforce, or the military.

Join an online Q&A session with SMSgt Quintana and students who can share their preservative of the JROTC class. Parents - check your email, links were sent through SchoolMessenger!

Next year 9th Graders - May 26, 2020 3:00 PM
Next year 10th Graders - May 27, 2020 3:00 PM
Next year Upperclassmen - May 28, 2020 03:00 PM

Questions, email: squintana@abs.misd.net

post_text: Interested in working with children? Have a passion or education and teaching? Want to explore careers in a school district? Anchor Bay High School offers a Teacher Cadet class for any Junior or Senior! The class is a 2 hour block (5th and 6th hour) and you work in a elementary or middle school classroom 3 days a week! text:
Anchor Bay High School DECA Chapter, under Adviser Mr. Bryan Mittelstadt traveled to downtown Detroit to compete in the 2020 Michigan State Career Development Conference. The conference consisted of individual and team business role play events and examinations related to specific fields of business. Eight students made the trip who qualified prior at the district competition.
Results from the state competition include:
- Jacob Yono, State Finalist, State Champion, moving onto Nationals, Sports and Entertainment Marketing.
- Ishaan Jain, State Finalist, State Champion, moving onto Nationals, Principals of Marketing
- Amanda Thompson, State Finalist,Restaurant & Food Service Management.
- Ben Seeley, Award in Economics Examination.

Jacob Yono and Ishaan Jain were to go to Nashville, Tennessee for the 2020 DECA International Career Development Conference representing not only Anchor Bay High School but the Michigan DECA Delegation.

Students do not need to be present, meals can be picked up for all children in the household at one location. Please share!!!!

post_text: Congratulations to the Anchor Bay High School 9th Grade Symphonic Band, Cadet/Concert Band, Symphonic Band, and Wind Ensemble for receiving an overall SUPERIOR First Division rating at the District 16 MSBOA Band Festival hosted at Anchor Bay High School. It is the 21st year in a row that the Wind Ensemble received a First Division, and the 23rd year in a row that the Symphonic Band received a First Division at this annual assessment for concert bands in the state of Michigan. We have many reasons to take pride in the accomplishments of our Anchor Bay School District student-musicians!

post_text: Sugarbush Elementary was visited by Ribbi the Mascot for the Eastside Diamond Hoppers of the United Shores Professional Baseball League. He came along with a few of his friends to encourage the students to work hard to achieve their reading goals they set for March is Reading Month. If they reach their goal, they will receive a ticket to a game, have their name announced and have an opportunity to run the bases. The students had fun participating in a few games and hearing a story about Ribbi.

post_text:
5th grade students at Lighthouse participated in “If You Can Dream It, You Can Do It” Essay Contest sponsored by the Pay It Forward Community Foundation. Many great ideas were shared!
>>>>>>> master
The winners’ topics that will be brought to life were:
1. Thankful Baskets for community members such as teachers, police, fire department.
2. Winter Boot Drive for children in the community who could use a pair of warm boots during the cold months.
3. School Garden to improve the outside space plus educate students about plants.

Additionally, no-sew blankets for those in need for members of our community will be made & distributed and a “feelings group” will be started.

We’re VERY proud of all the ways 5th grade Lighthouse writers showed they can be the “I” in K*ND to pay it forward in our community!!!

P.S. the answer to “What do you do with an idea?”....

YOU
CHANGE
THE
WORLD!
❤️ 🌎

post_text: Lighthouse Green Team had guest speaker Jerry Hasspacher visit and share "Let's Go Green" a presentation on Dark Skies, energy conservation, protecting wildlife and the watershed, and native species vs. invasive species. He is a member of The Southeast Michigan Group of the Sierra Club. Students learned some new ways to reduce negative impacts on our environment.

post_text: Captain Dan Woodward of Blue Line Charters, from Brighton, Michigan, was the featured speaker at the February monthly meeting of the Anchor Bay Fishing Club at MS North. Captain Keith Krych, was scheduled to present, however, he passed away last fall and Captain Dan volunteered to present in his honor. Captain Dan presented in front of a packed library, with over 60 students and parents. He covered basic walleye trolling tactics and Off Shore Tackle trolling equipment in open water. For the kids only, free raffle table, he brought over $150 worth of prizes, many donated by Off Shore Tackle. Thanks Captain Dan!

post_text: As part of their Positive Behavior Support program, Sugarbush Elementary celebrates a different positive theme each month. The focus for the month of February is Respect. To help promote the theme Mrs. White, the principal, reads each class a book about the theme and leads the students in a discussion to make connections to their own life.

post_text:
On Friday, February 7th, the Anchor Bay High School Jazz Ensemble took part in the 47th annual Phi Mu Alpha/Central Michigan University Jazz Weekend. The festival featured over 60 of the best high school jazz bands and combos from around the state of Michigan.
>>>>>>> master

Congratulations to all ABHS Jazz Ensemble student-musicians! As part of the group's overall outstanding performance, the Anchor Bay HS Jazz Ensemble was awarded the festival’s top spot by receiving the “Overall Best Band” Award in the Class AA division. In addition to the overall ensemble recognition, the ABHS Jazz Ensemble’s Trombone Section was awarded with the festival’s “Overall Best Section” Award in Class AA. Senior, Blake Brdak (guitar), added to the awards by receiving the Class AA “First Runner-Up Best Soloist” Award. This recognition marks the 19th time in the past 23 years that Anchor Bay HS has received a major award at this prestigious event hosting the state’s best high school jazz ensembles and combos. It is the 6th time the school has been awarded the top overall band award.
text:
On Friday, February 7th, the Anchor Bay High School Jazz Ensemble took part in the 47th annual Phi Mu Alpha/Central Michigan University Jazz Weekend. The festival featured over 60 of the best high school jazz bands and combos from around the state of Michigan.

Congratulations to all ABHS Jazz Ensemble student-musicians! As part of the group's overall outstanding performance, the Anchor Bay HS Jazz Ensemble was awarded the festival’s top spot by receiving the “Overall Best Band” Award in the Class AA division. In addition to the overall ensemble recognition, the ABHS Jazz Ensemble’s Trombone Section was awarded with the festival’s “Overall Best Section” Award in Class AA. Senior, Blake Brdak (guitar), added to the awards by receiving the Class AA “First Runner-Up Best Soloist” Award. This recognition marks the 19th time in the past 23 years that Anchor Bay HS has received a major award at this prestigious event hosting the state’s best high school jazz ensembles and combos. It is the 6th time the school has been awarded the top overall band award.

post_text: Congratulations to the 97 ABHS instrumental music students who participated in this year’s MSBOA District XVI Solo and Ensemble Festival. These student-musicians worked after school and over the weekend to prepare for their performances. The festival took place Saturday, January 25th, Friday, January 31st, and Saturday, February 1st, at Rochester High School with entries being judged by one of over 40 experts on musical performance and ability. The 54 events who received a First Division rating qualified for the MSBOA State Solo & Ensemble Festival in March.

post_text: On Saturday January 25th, 63 students from Anchor Bay MS North and MS South participated in the annual MSBOA District XVI Solo & Ensemble Festival at Rochester HS. At this event, approximately 3,000 band and orchestra students from Macomb, Oakland, & St. Clair counties perform a prepared solo or small ensemble (duet, trio, quartet, etc.) for adjudicators. Following their performance, students receive valuable feedback from the adjudicators and are given a rating from 1st Division (highest) down to 5th Division. The Anchor Bay Band Program would like to congratulate all participants and express how proud we are of your accomplishments.

post_text: Mark Sak, was the featured speaker at the January monthly meeting for the Anchor Bay Fishing Club. Mark is an acclaimed Outdoor Writer and Pro Angler that competed in the Professional Walleye Tour (PWT) and ice fishing tournaments. Additionally, Mark is a professional writer covering hunting and fishing, Woods-N-Water News, as well as pro staff for Jiffy Ice Drills. Mark's presentation covered ways the club can help in local conservation and protecting our fishery, especially for commercial fishing. Additionally, Mark covered ice fishing equipment and safety. Thanks Mark for donating your time to our club!

post_text: Anchor Bay School Liaison Officer, Officer DePape, presented on Social Media and Anti-Bullying lessons to students in 3rd, 4th and 5th grade. She taught them about their "digital footprint" online and the difference between conflicts and bullying. Officer DePape gave students problem solving scenarios and they practiced using the "Debug System" that included how to get adult help. We are fortunate to have this resource for our students. Together we can help keep our kids safe! #tarspirit

post_text: Kaleidoscope Contest Winner: Congratulations Angelica Medley from Middle School North, 6th Grade - Mrs. Simon's class, for her work called "Two Sides." Each year students in every elementary school and middle school are encouraged to submit an entry for the Michigan Reading Association Kaleidoscope contest. Entries are judged by a panel at each school and one winner is selected. These young authors and their families, along with the winners from around the state, will be invited to attend the Michigan Reading Association luncheon in the winter to honor their accomplishment. In addition, all school winners will have their work published in the 2020 Kaleidoscope book.

This letter was just emailed to parents and staff:

Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) Information

We are aware that some Anchor Bay families and staff are concerned about the Novel Coronavirus. This virus causes mild to severe respiratory illness with fever, cough, and difficulty breathing. According to the state health department, test results of four possible 2019 Novel Coronavirus (Wuhan Virus) cases in Michigan came back negative. Even without a confirmed coronavirus case here in Michigan, we wanted to be proactive with information since we do have 49 students at Anchor Bay High School from China.

Here are a few facts to help calm any concerns. All of our students are from Beijing (over 700…

post_text: Kaleidoscope Contest Winner: Congratulations Emmett Schwartz from Naldrett Elementary, 4th Grade - Mrs. Sacker's class, for his work called "Waffles". Each year students in every elementary school and middle school are encouraged to submit an entry for the Michigan Reading Association Kaleidoscope contest. Entries are judged by a panel at each school and one winner is selected. These young authors and their families, along with the winners from around the state, will be invited to attend the Michigan Reading Association luncheon in the winter to honor their accomplishment. In addition, all school winners will have their work published in the 2020 Kaleidoscope book. We will post winners on this Facebook page through out the week!

post_text:
Anchor Bay Fishing Club field trip!
What do anglers do when there’s ice and snow? Go to fishing shows. Some student in the ABFC took a trip to the Ultimate Fishing Show at Suburban Collection Showplace in Novi. Students checked out the newest angling techniques, baits, and gear. The show is a great way to be a better angler by attending different presentations and meeting vendors. By far the bait claw machine was a hit with the students!

text:
Congratulations to the ABHS DECA team! They earned 14 medals and 6 invites to DECA State Competition.

Dylan Boehm earned gold and a state invite for Financial Decision Making. Faith Horwath earned gold in Quick Service Management. Amanda Thompson earned blue, gold and a state invite for Restaurant and Food Service Management. Jacob Yono earned blue, gold and a state invite in Sports Marketing. Ishaan Jain earned a state invite in Principles of Marketing. Jason Dandurand earned a blue medal in Buying and Merchandising. Congratulations to all!!

Name: Emily Hall

Degree/Endorsements: Elementary Education (Mathematics)

Previous work experience: Third grade at the STEAM Academy at Woodrow Wilson

Hobbies/What do you do in your spare time: In my spare time, I enjoy hiking and going on any outdoor adventure. I also love to take my dog on walks and exercise.

What do you like about working at Anchor Bay: I love working at Anchor Bay because of the support I receive as a new teaching to the building. Each staff member has taken their time to help, or even just offer words of encouragement. The building is truly a family and they all take care of each other.

Positive event/experience that has happened in your first few months here: My most positive experience has been seeing the growth within each of my students. I feel very blessed to be a teacher and play a small part in each of their lives / education.

text:
Today is National Law Enforcement Appreciation Day! Superintendent Leonard Woodside would like to thank our local police chiefs for the support of our schools and providing resource officers that interact with our students on a daily basis - keeping them safe and building positive relationships.

Thank you to St. Clair County Sheriff Tim Donnellon, New Baltimore Chief Michael Mertens, Chesterfield Chief Bradley Kersten, and Clay Township Chief Michael Koach, Macomb County Sheriff and Michigan State Police.

Special thanks to our School Resource Officers: Saint Clair County Sheriff Deputy Fajardo , Chesterfield Police Officer DePape, and New Baltimore Officer LeBeau.

post_text: Last month MSN Competitive Cheer Team did a packing night for Feed the Bay. Each school year, approximately 1 in 4 students in the Anchor Bay School District qualify for the Free and Reduced Lunch Program. The goal of the Feed the Bay Backpack Program is to ensure that every at-risk student in the Anchor Bay School District has access to food over the weekend, so that they show up at school on Monday, well-nourished and ready to learn. To find out more, visit their Facebook page at: facebook.com/feedthebaynb.

post_text: The Anchor Bay Fishing Club December meeting speaker was Captain Ken Clark of Fishmas Charters from Whitehall, Michigan. He presented his tournament winning technique with the Jigging Rapala bait to the members.The Chesterfield Cabela’s conference room was filled up with over 40 students and parents in attendance. Captain Ken drove over 200 miles to present to the club and every student left with free baits. Thanks Captain Ken! Stay tuned to see who the next top-notch speaker will be for the ABFC!

post_text: Ms. Turner's 8th grade Social Studies students at Anchor Bay Middle School North did an escape room about the War of 1812. They had to use their prior knowledge about the war, critical thinking skills, and collaboration skills to solve the puzzles in 40 minutes. The clues were spread around the room and they could only work on one clue at a time. The students worked with their table mates to decode the clues and when they were finished, some wanted to take a photo op with some signs that are used in escape rooms. The students loved it and they all did a great job working with their team.
